The Silence: What It Is
Not a technique. Not a word. Not a sound.

The Silence is the ability to remove something from the world. Not to command. Not to control. To unmake.

When a person trained in The Silence speaks—not with words, but with intent—they can remove something temporarily. A guard's memory of seeing them. A soldier's ability to draw a blade. An enemy's understanding of where they are standing.

It doesn't create. It erases. For a moment. Just long enough.

How It Works
The Training: Years of learning to empty the self. To become nothing. To hold in your mind not what you want to happen, but what you want not to be there. The order teaches this. The mother learned it. She used it too many times.

The Cost: Every use leaves a scar on the user's throat. Not visible. Something deeper. Use it too many times, and the ability to make any sound begins to fade. Use it too many times after that, and the ability to speak at all disappears.

The mother used The Silence to protect her children. Multiple times. In ways they never knew. She traded her voice for their lives.

What It Looks Like
At the knife-at-the-neck moment: The user doesn't move. Doesn't speak. They empty themselves. The attacker's blade is at their throat. And in that instant, the attacker forgets why they were holding it. Not their purpose. Not their hatred. Just... the moment. The blade wavers. The user moves.

In the dead twin's return: She enters the room. The Silent Court is there. The order is there. She does not speak. She looks at one of them—the one who accepted her father's bond. That member opens their mouth to speak. Nothing comes out. The Silence has taken their voice. Not permanently. For now. Long enough for everyone in the room to understand: she is not here to ask. She is here to take.

